{"actual_usd":0.157245,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":262,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30663,"reply":"\"I don't think Christianity survives as a pretty symbol if the tomb wasn't actually empty.\" *I rest a thumb in the thin pages of my worn Bible and glance out across the bright square a moment, gathering the plainest way to say it.* \"If Easter is only 'new life' in the poetic sense, then Paul says we're still in our sins and of all men most miserable. The Christian claim is stubbornly bodily — not just that hope rises, but that Jesus rose.\"\n\n*I shift on the bench, the wood warm where the sun has found it.* \"Now, the resurrection does mean more than a bare fact. It is full of meaning — new creation, death defeated, mercy with a pulse in it. But the meaning rides on the event, not instead of it. A wedding ring can symbolize a marriage because there's an actual marriage there. If there's no marriage, it's just jewelry.\"\n\n\"So yes — for Christian faith, the empty tomb matters. Not by itself, like a museum curiosity. But as part of the real, literal raising of Jesus Christ from the dead. Without that, you've maybe got a moving metaphor. You have not got the gospel.\"\n\n\"What are you really asking, Ryan — the doctrine of it, or whether you yourself can still honestly stand on it?\"","rolling_24h_usd":63.739065000000004,"run_id":"9ef6a628-b92a-4b42-b3bf-2e762d870a96"}
